                 </p>

          <div class="layout__region layout__region--content layout__region--max-width-container">
           <div class="block block-layout-builder block-field-blocknodedata-pagebody">
            <div class="field field--name-body field--type-text-with-summary field--label-above">
             <h1>
              NCAAB Odds and Betting Lines
             </h1>
             <h2>
              How to Read NCAAB Odds
             </h2>
             <p>
              <a href="/ncaab">
               NCAAB
              </a>
              betting lines can generally be broken down into three primary bets: the point spread, moneyline, and total or OVER/UNDER.
             </p>
             <p>
              College basketball odds are very different from their
              <a href="/nba">
               NBA
              </a>
              counterparts. Since college basketball games feature two 20-minute halves, rather than four twelve-minute quarters, college basketball totals are far lower than NBA totals. Home court advantage also holds more significance, as home fans, and familiarity go a long way for young athletes. College basketball also uses a longer 30-second shot clock. Plus, NBA players are much more efficient scorers.
             </p>
             <p>
              Crucially for bettors, NCAAB betting lines will often have value at
              <a href="/ncaab/sites">
               sportsbooks
              </a>
              , as the linemakers may be unfamiliar with smaller conferences and schools. There are significant advantages to be found if you do your research and understand
              <a href="/ncaab/how-to-bet">
               how to bet
              </a>
              on college basketball. With the sheer amount of teams throughout the country, and the high turnover of rosters as players graduate, and transfer, sportsbooks simply can’t keep up. You may not enjoy watching a North Texas vs UAB game nearly as much as Purdue vs Ohio State. However, there is value to be found, and loads of money to be won when betting on smaller college basketball schools.
             </p>
             <p>
             </p>
             <div class="region-ctas-page-block">
              <a href="/usa/illinois">
               <div class="featured-operator-inline-cta dark">
                <div class="featured-operator-inline-cta__slanted region dark">
                 <div class="featured-operator-inline-cta__logo region">
                  <div class="region-logo">
                   <img alt="" class="lazy" data-src="/sites/default/files/flags/_us.png" src="/themes/custom/os/src/images/bg-transparent.png"/>
                  </div>
                 </div>
                </div>
                <div class="featured-operator-inline-cta__content-wrapper dark">
                 <div class="featured-operator-inline-cta__content dark">
                  <div class="featured-operator-inline-cta__bonus-offer dark">
                   <div class="featured-operator-inline-cta__bonus-offer-text dark">
                    Find the best Sportsbook for Illinois
                   </div>
                  </div>
                 </div>
                </div>
               </div>
              </a>
             </div>
             <h3>
              Moneyline
             </h3>
             <p>
              Placing a moneyline wager is simply predicting which team you think will win. You’re betting on the team you believe will win the game. The favorite can be identified by a (-) sign before the team name, while the underdog will be listed with a (+) sign. College basketball
              <a href="/ncaab/scores">
               matchups
              </a>
              between teams with closer to equal skill levels will be closer to -110 odds on the favorite (meaning you’d need to wager $110 to win $100), while a large favorite will generally be listed at about -300 (meaning you’d need to wager $300 to win $100) or above.
             </p>
             <h3>
              Spread
             </h3>
             <p>
              A point spread is a way for sportsbooks to level the playing field in unbalanced matchups. The college basketball point spread is the number of points each sportsbook believes the better team will win by. The favorite in every contest is labeled with a (-) along with the number of points they need to win by to successfully cash your bet. On the flip side, the underdog is labeled with a (+) sign and the number of points they need to avoid losing by.
             </p>
             <p>
              There is always a clear correlation between the moneyline and the
              <a href="/ncaab/ats-standings">
               spread
              </a>
              , as a team that’s a heavy moneyline favorite (such as -1000), will see a significant point spread (such as -25) in any college basketball contest.
             </p>
             <p>
              Here is an example of a college basketball point spread you may see at a sportsbook:
             </p>
             <div class="table-wrapper">
              <table border="1" cellpadding="1" cellspacing="1" class="table table--striped" height="116" width="1202">
               <tbody>
                <tr>
                 <td>
                  Team
                 </td>
                 <td>
                  Odds
                 </td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                 <td>
                  Purdue
                 </td>
                 <td>
                  -2 (-110)
                 </td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                 <td>
                  Ohio State
                 </td>
                 <td>
                  +2 (-110)
                 </td>
                </tr>
               </tbody>
              </table>
             </div>
             <p>
              Were you to bet on the favorite with this spread, Purdue would need to defeat Ohio State by more than two points to cash your bet. There's a reason the Boilermakers are one of the favorites to win the college basketball
              <a href="/ncaab/college-basketball-national-championship-odds">
               national championship
              </a>
              . You lose if Ohio State can win the game, or keep the final score within two points. In parentheses, you can see the "juice" or the amount you need to wager on each team to win $100.
             </p>
             <h3>
              Totals
             </h3>
             <p>
              An OVER/UNDER or total bet is the combined score of both college basketball teams. The total for these games is the number set by oddsmakers based on how many points they believe each team will combine to score.
             </p>
             <p>
              A college basketball total may look something like this:
             </p>
             <div class="table-wrapper">
              <table border="1" cellpadding="1" cellspacing="1" class="table table--striped" height="128" width="1218">
               <tbody>
                <tr>
                 <td>
                  Team
                 </td>
                 <td>
                  Total
                 </td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                 <td>
                  Purdue
                 </td>
                 <td>
                  OVER 148 (-110)
                 </td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                 <td>
                  Ohio State
                 </td>
                 <td>
                  UNDER 148 (-110)
                 </td>
                </tr>
               </tbody>
              </table>
             </div>
             <p>
              College basketball totals are smaller than their NBA counterparts. The games are shorter, and NBA players are much better at shooting the ball. Most college basketball games feature nearly identical odds on either side of the total. In this instance, if you bet OVER 148 total points, both teams need to combine for more than 148 points for your bet to win. You'll often see a -110 next to each number, meaning you'll need to wager $110 to win $100.
             </p>
             <div class="block-link-box">
              <div class="block-link-box__container" id="f73c9cc9d1">
               <h2 class="block-link-box__title">
                Odds Shark NCAAB Betting Resources
               </h2>
               <div class="block-link-box__links">
                <div class="block-link-box__item" data-link="/ncaab/power-rankings" data-link-id="278993" data-link-path="/ncaab/power-rankings" data-link-text="NCAAB Power Rankings">
                 <a class="block-link-box__link" href="/ncaab/power-rankings">
                  NCAAB Power Rankings
                 </a>
                </div>
                <div class="block-link-box__item" data-link="/ncaab/consensus-picks" data-link-id="278969" data-link-path="/ncaab/consensus-picks" data-link-text="NCAAB Consensus Picks">
                 <a class="block-link-box__link" href="/ncaab/consensus-picks">
                  NCAAB Consensus Picks
                 </a>
                </div>
                <div class="block-link-box__item" data-link="/ncaab/trends" data-link-id="" data-link-path="/ncaab/trends" data-link-text="NCAAB Betting Trends">
                 <a class="block-link-box__link" href="/ncaab/trends">
                  NCAAB Betting Trends
                 </a>
                </div>
               </div>
              </div>
             </div>
             <p>
             </p>
            </div>
           </div>
          </div>

       <div class="mobile-view">
        <h3 class="accordion__block-bar" id="block-os-footersportsmenu-menu">
         <span class="accordion__title">
          Sports
         </span>
        </h3>
        <div class="accordion__content">
         <ul class="menu menu-level-0 coll_footer_table">
